Model Basics: Nonagricultural Employment

MPA 634: Data Science for Managers

20 November 2019

This R Markdown document requires the forecast, fImport, timeSeries, magrittr, and car libraries. For this reason, you may need to install them in order for you to be able to execute the code.

Modeling and forecasting steps using an exploratory approach

  1. Become familiar with the data using graphs
  2. Identify families of models that might be appropriate
  3. Estimate the models
  4. Check the residuals to see if information remains
  5. Use the model to make forecasts

Example: Forecast of not seasonally adjusted nonagricultural employment

Obtain the data from FRED

jobs <- fredSeries('PAYNSA', from = "1980-01-01") %>%
  as.ts() %>% 
  divide_by(1000)

Draw a picture of the data

jobs %>% 
  ggtsdisplay()

Remove the trend

jobs %>% 
  diff(lag = 1) %>% 
  ggtsdisplay()

Remove the trend and seasonality

jobs %>% 
  diff(lag = 1) %>% 
  diff(lag = 12) %>% 
  ggtsdisplay()

Possible model families

  1. Season and Trend with Loess (STL)
  2. Exponetial smoothing or state space modeling
  3. Auto-regressive Integrated Moving Average (ARIMA)

Use the additive decomposition model to separate the time series into:

  • Trend
  • Seasonality
  • Remainder
jobs_stl <- jobs %>% 
  stl(s.window = 7)
jobs_stl %>%
  str()

Result of the decomposition

jobs_stl %>% 
  autoplot() +
  labs(
    title = "STL decomposition of time series"
  )

Information in STL residuals?

jobs_stl$time.series[, "remainder"] %>% 
  ggtsdisplay()

Prediction using the STL model

jobs_stl %>%
  forecast(h = 24) %>% 
  autoplot()

ETS is part of the family of state space models. These models are also known as exponential smoothing.

ETS doesn’t extract all of the information from the data. Information remains in the residuals

jobs_ets %>% 
  residuals() %>% 
  ggtsdisplay()

Forecasting with the ETS model

jobs_ets %>% 
  forecast(h = 24) %>% 
  autoplot()

ARIMA model

Human diagnosis

jobs_human <- jobs %>% 
  arima(order = c(3, 1, 0), seasonal = c(1, 1, 0))
jobs_human %>% 
  checkresiduals()

## 
##  Ljung-Box test
## 
## data:  Residuals from ARIMA(3,1,0)(1,1,0)[12]
## Q* = 46.6, df = 20, p-value = 0.0006664
## 
## Model df: 4.   Total lags used: 24
forecast(jobs_human, h = 24) %>%
  as.ts() %>% 
  autoplot()

Machine learning

jobs_machine <- jobs %>% 
  auto.arima()
jobs_machine %>% 
  checkresiduals()

## 
##  Ljung-Box test
## 
## data:  Residuals from ARIMA(2,0,2)(1,1,2)[12] with drift
## Q* = 16.367, df = 16, p-value = 0.4277
## 
## Model df: 8.   Total lags used: 24
jobs_machine %>% 
  forecast(h = 24) %>% 
  autoplot()
